‐ I set my first weld.
It takes.

10:22.705 --> 10:23.998
<i>Flux a little more,</i>
<i>throw it back‐‐</i>

10:23.998 --> 10:26.543
<i>just for an insurance policy.</i>

10:26.543 --> 10:28.336
<i>So now, for the first time</i>
<i>in the competition,</i>

10:28.336 --> 10:31.256
<i>I start trying</i>
<i>to shape my blade.</i>

10:31.256 --> 10:32.924
<i>I'm feeling pretty good about</i>
<i>the shape that I'm getting,</i>

10:32.924 --> 10:34.175
so this is it.

10:34.175 --> 10:37.303
<i>I need to get this thing</i>
<i>in the quench.</i>

10:37.303 --> 10:39.222
‐ The quench from Mike
with a really,

10:39.222 --> 10:41.307
really hot blade, man.

10:41.307 --> 10:44.769
That thing was
the temperature of the sun.

10:44.769 --> 10:46.187
It had to have been.
‐ [laughs]

10:46.187 --> 10:47.480
<i>And with that amount of heat,</i>

10:47.480 --> 10:49.315
<i>I'd be really surprised</i>
<i>if it didn't warp.</i>

10:49.315 --> 10:52.110
‐ Watch those San Mai edges
just go, "Boink!"

10:52.110 --> 10:56.072
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:56.072 --> 10:58.825
<i>‐ I've got my pieces of steel</i>
<i>in the forge,</i>

10:58.825 --> 11:01.411
<i>and I start trying to get</i>

11:01.411 --> 11:04.164
<i>a basic bolo shape</i>
<i>into the steel.</i>

11:04.164 --> 11:06.749
‐ That whole piece he's got
there is 7 inches long.

11:06.749 --> 11:09.502
<i>And I don't know</i>
<i>if it's long enough.</i>

11:09.502 --> 11:10.879
‐ 15 minutes!

11:10.879 --> 11:14.299
<i>‐ I feel the weight</i>
<i>of the time over me,</i>

11:14.299 --> 11:16.092
<i>and I want to finish.</i>

11:16.092 --> 11:18.595
I want to make this look good.

11:18.595 --> 11:21.598
<i>And then once</i>
<i>I have a bolo shape,</i>

11:21.598 --> 11:23.308
<i>I have to quench.</i>

11:23.308 --> 11:27.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.228 --> 11:31.191
<i>My blade gets hard.</i>
<i>It's somewhat bolo‐shaped.</i>

11:31.191 --> 11:33.359
<i>And I'd like to say</i>
<i>it's not bad.</i>

11:33.359 --> 11:35.361
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.361 --> 11:38.239
‐ The second quench went good.
I got a good, straight blade,

11:38.239 --> 11:39.782
<i>I start to put in my bevels.</i>

11:39.782 --> 11:42.785
That's when I notice the delam.

11:42.785 --> 11:46.247
‐ Joe's really, really
examining his steel over here.

11:46.247 --> 11:48.291
I wonder if there's an issue.

11:48.291 --> 11:50.376
<i>‐ At this point in time,</i>
<i>if I'm at my home forge,</i>

11:50.376 --> 11:53.755
<i>this is going into the scrap</i>
<i>pile and I'm starting over.</i>

11:53.755 --> 11:55.131
I could put a Band‐Aid on it,

11:55.131 --> 11:56.674
but I'm not really
fixing the problem.

11:56.674 --> 11:59.177
<i>I very well could be</i>
<i>the one going home.</i>

11:59.177 --> 12:01.262
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:01.262 --> 12:03.932
‐ So I go in for my quench.
I pull my blade out.

12:03.932 --> 12:06.601
<i>I realize that the blade</i>
<i>didn't fully harden.</i>

12:06.601 --> 12:08.019
Ah, [bleep].

12:08.019 --> 12:09.437
<i>So, with four minutes</i>
<i>on the clock,</i>

12:09.437 --> 12:12.065
<i>I go back in</i>
<i>for a second quench.</i>

12:12.065 --> 12:18.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:18.279 --> 12:20.240
Oh, [bleep].

12:20.240 --> 12:22.242
Just dropped that in there.

12:22.242 --> 12:24.327
‐ Matt's blade
is laying in the bottom

12:24.327 --> 12:26.079
of his oil drum over there.

12:26.079 --> 12:27.497
I mean, he's quenched it.

12:27.497 --> 12:28.957
<i>‐ I put my finger in the oil.</i>

12:28.957 --> 12:31.584
Oh, it's hot‐‐didn't really
want to put my arm in there.

12:31.584 --> 12:33.628
‐ Five, four,

12:33.628 --> 12:36.547
three, two, one.

12:36.547 --> 12:37.966
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

12:37.966 --> 12:39.175
Drop your tools.

12:39.175 --> 12:42.303
This first round
of competition is over.

12:42.303 --> 12:44.597
[applause]

12:44.597 --> 12:46.391
<i>‐ Round's over and</i>
<i>I don't know where I stand.</i>

12:46.391 --> 12:48.101
You know, I definitely
didn't expect to be

12:48.101 --> 12:50.353
screwing around with some gear
for an hour and half

12:50.353 --> 12:52.939
and then struggling to quench.

12:52.939 --> 12:54.649
<i>This is definitely one</i>
<i>of the toughest challenges</i>

12:54.649 --> 12:56.651
<i>that I've ever faced.</i>

12:56.651 --> 12:58.278
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:58.278 --> 13:01.406
‐ Bladesmiths, this first round
of competition is complete.

13:01.406 --> 13:04.826
You guys are here jockeying
for the air force anvil

13:04.826 --> 13:07.954
in our Battle of the Branches
final competition.

13:07.954 --> 13:09.205
Now it's time for the judges

13:09.205 --> 13:10.999
to take a closer look
at your work.

13:10.999 --> 13:12.166
Matt, you're up first.

13:12.166 --> 13:13.960
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:13.960 --> 13:16.963
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:16.963 --> 13:20.758
‐ [laughs] You did it!
Boy, was I worried for a while.

13:20.758 --> 13:22.677
Took a long time
fighting with that steel,

13:22.677 --> 13:24.137
trying to get it to come apart

13:24.137 --> 13:26.014
and get a small enough
piece to work with.

13:26.014 --> 13:27.807
I really commend you
for sticking to it

13:27.807 --> 13:29.309
and pushing through.

13:29.309 --> 13:31.686
This looks and feels like

13:31.686 --> 13:33.980
a pretty solid piece of metal.

13:33.980 --> 13:35.398
Down here, in the tang,

13:35.398 --> 13:37.650
there's a lot of stuff
going on.

13:37.650 --> 13:39.861
But whoo‐hoo,
it's a slab‐handled knife,

13:39.861 --> 13:42.155
which covers a lot of flaws.
‐ [laughs]

13:42.155 --> 13:45.575
‐ So, I don't see
anything, honestly,

13:45.575 --> 13:48.327
other than the
curvature of this blade

13:48.327 --> 13:50.830
that really can't be
dealt with. Good job.

13:50.830 --> 13:52.248
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Joe, you're up.

13:52.248 --> 13:54.208
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:54.208 --> 13:56.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:56.419 --> 13:59.589
<i>‐ You do have a bolo profile.</i>

13:59.589 --> 14:02.050
It's got a nice handle shape,
a nice handle size,

14:02.050 --> 14:04.010
but there's a big issue.

14:04.010 --> 14:06.679
<i>There's a quite‐‐</i>
<i>a large delamination.</i>

14:06.679 --> 14:10.433
It's split at the end here.
It's forked over.

14:10.433 --> 14:15.271
It comes back a lot of the way
where it's still not connected.

14:15.271 --> 14:17.315
I don't know how far up
this issue goes,

14:17.315 --> 14:21.235
but you may find that grinding
one side and cutting off

14:21.235 --> 14:24.989
this big old part
coming off to one side here

14:24.989 --> 14:26.866
could leave you with
some steel that's usable.

14:26.866 --> 14:29.202
‐ Thank you.
‐ Mike, you're up next.

14:29.202 --> 14:32.121
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:32.121 --> 14:33.706
<i>‐ Well, Mike,</i>
<i>you nailed the shape.</i>

14:33.706 --> 14:37.251
<i>I like the fact that it has</i>
<i>that real subtle recurve</i>

14:37.251 --> 14:39.712
<i>that a bolo has,</i>
<i>yet a straight back.</i>

14:39.712 --> 14:42.090
But when I'm looking
at the seams on one side,

14:42.090 --> 14:44.759
there's some delamination
up here right at the very edge,

14:44.759 --> 14:46.636
but I'm guessing that
as you grind that back,

14:46.636 --> 14:48.763
you're gonna get rid of
those pretty quickly.

14:48.763 --> 14:50.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:50.515 --> 14:52.225
‐ All right, Mike,
the one thing

14:52.225 --> 14:54.811
I'm having an issue right now
with is this handle.

14:54.811 --> 14:57.146
Grabbing onto it right now,
that belly you have right there

14:57.146 --> 14:59.607
forces my hand
to open up a little bit.

14:59.607 --> 15:01.442
So, when you're gonna
add on scales to this,

15:01.442 --> 15:02.860
it makes it even bigger.

15:02.860 --> 15:05.238
So, think about that when
you're holding onto this.

15:05.238 --> 15:07.240
‐ All right.

15:07.240 --> 15:11.202
‐ Daren, there's a major
problem with your blade.

15:11.202 --> 15:14.330
<i>Your bolo was supposed to have</i>
<i>been between 9 and 11 inches</i>

15:14.330 --> 15:16.124
<i>for the tip to plunge grind,</i>

15:16.124 --> 15:19.252
and your blade is coming up
short at 8 3/8 inches.

15:19.252 --> 15:22.171
That is grounds for immediate
dismissal from this forge.

15:22.171 --> 15:23.923
For that reason,
I have to ask you to please

15:23.923 --> 15:26.259
surrender your weapon
and leave The Forge.

15:26.259 --> 15:30.429
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:30.429 --> 15:32.348
<i>‐ Coming here was</i>
<i>definitely a risk for me‐‐</i>

15:32.348 --> 15:34.183
took me out of my comfort zone.

15:34.183 --> 15:35.935
<i>If you don't take risks,</i>

15:35.935 --> 15:37.603
you'll never
accomplish anything.

15:37.603 --> 15:39.939
<i>I may not be in the</i>
<i>competition anymore,</i>

15:39.939 --> 15:41.399
but these guys,
they're gonna be here

15:41.399 --> 15:43.860
representing the rest of us
air force guys.

15:43.860 --> 15:45.528
<i>And in the end,</i>
<i>I'm sure we'll see him</i>

15:45.528 --> 15:48.531
<i>standing on top of the pile.</i>

15:48.531 --> 15:50.616
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
Congratulations.

15:50.616 --> 15:53.327
You've made it into the second
round of this competition.

15:53.327 --> 15:54.787
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

15:54.787 --> 15:56.789
it's time to turn them
into fully functional bolos

15:56.789 --> 15:59.125
by attaching handles to them
and address the flaws

15:59.125 --> 16:01.043
and issues that were identified
in your blades.

16:01.043 --> 16:02.461
Additionally, gentlemen,

16:02.461 --> 16:04.797
three pin holes,
a lanyard hole,

16:04.797 --> 16:06.632
and an acid etch
on your blades.

16:06.632 --> 16:08.676
After this round,
we'll be testing your blades

16:08.676 --> 16:10.219
for strength and durability

16:10.219 --> 16:12.930
<i>in a flight helmet chop</i>

16:12.930 --> 16:15.933
and for edge retention
in a sugarcane slice.

16:15.933 --> 16:17.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.602 --> 16:19.312
Do your best work,
and I remind you that

16:19.312 --> 16:21.063
after your blades
have been tested,

16:21.063 --> 16:22.857
one of you will have
to surrender your bolo

16:22.857 --> 16:24.358
and leave The Forge.

16:24.358 --> 16:26.986
Good luck.
Your two hours starts now.

16:26.986 --> 16:28.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:28.571 --> 16:31.032
<i>‐ I'm thinking, I can do</i>
<i>all this stuff in three hours,</i>

16:31.032 --> 16:32.533
<i>and then Wil says two.</i>

16:32.533 --> 16:35.661
And I just know my face says,
"Oh, [bleep]."

16:35.661 --> 16:38.915
<i>For the handle, I decided to</i>
<i>go with a tan Micarta material</i>

16:38.915 --> 16:42.210
because it most closely matches
the wood of the original,

16:42.210 --> 16:44.587
but the material
is just tough as nails.

16:44.587 --> 16:48.007
‐ These guys have
a lot of flaws to deal with.

16:48.007 --> 16:49.759
‐ The judges were talking about

16:49.759 --> 16:51.802
<i>how big and oversized</i>
<i>my handle was.</i>

16:51.802 --> 16:53.262
[machine whirring]

16:53.262 --> 16:55.431
‐ Wow, Mike is doing some
aggressive grinding over there.

16:55.431 --> 16:57.350
‐ Ah, he's got a lot
of material there to grind.

16:57.350 --> 16:58.851
‐ Yep.

16:58.851 --> 17:01.520
<i>‐ After the handle, I've gotta</i>
<i>thin out the main blade.</i>

17:01.520 --> 17:04.065
The reason I waited to do that
instead of doing it all at once

17:04.065 --> 17:05.691
is I wanna get
my handle glued up.

17:05.691 --> 17:06.859
<i>Because while</i>
<i>the glue is curing,</i>

17:06.859 --> 17:08.361
<i>I can still work on</i>
<i>the rest of this.</i>

17:08.361 --> 17:11.197
<i>It won't slow me down at all.</i>

17:11.197 --> 17:13.074
<i>‐ Matt‐‐not only does</i>
<i>he have the curvature</i>

17:13.074 --> 17:14.700
<i>going in the wrong direction,</i>

17:14.700 --> 17:17.745
but like, the blade is also
windier than a snake's back.

17:17.745 --> 17:18.996
‐ Yeah.

17:18.996 --> 17:20.206
‐ So, I've got a warp
in my blade,

17:20.206 --> 17:22.208
<i>but I think</i>
<i>I'm gonna work that last</i>

17:22.208 --> 17:23.834
'cause I at least wanna
be able to turn in something

17:23.834 --> 17:27.255
that they can test,
so I gotta get a handle put on.

17:27.255 --> 17:30.216
<i>Also, by flipping</i>
<i>the blade upside down,</i>

17:30.216 --> 17:33.302
<i>I already can see that it's</i>
<i>gonna be much more manageable</i>

17:33.302 --> 17:35.888
to grind this bolo profile out.

17:35.888 --> 17:38.391
<i>Along with that, I need to</i>
<i>grind down the handle area</i>

17:38.391 --> 17:40.476
<i>'cause I have some</i>
<i>pretty deep grooves,</i>

17:40.476 --> 17:42.770
so handle scales aren't
gonna fit on very well.

17:42.770 --> 17:44.397
The clock is ticking and
I'm just trying to get this

17:44.397 --> 17:46.315
to where it needs to be
so they can test it.

17:46.315 --> 17:49.860
<i>Feeling pretty nervous</i>
<i>right now.</i>

17:49.860 --> 17:51.862
<i>‐ I wanna work on getting</i>
<i>a handle fitted up,</i>

17:51.862 --> 17:53.114
get it in place.

17:53.114 --> 17:54.740
My epoxy can be setting
in the first half hour

17:54.740 --> 17:56.701
<i>and dedicate the rest</i>
<i>of my time to my wood,</i>

17:56.701 --> 17:58.494
<i>'cause I obviously got</i>
<i>some very significant issues</i>

17:58.494 --> 17:59.996
<i>if I'm gonna make this work.</i>

17:59.996 --> 18:02.290
‐ On Joe's blade, I mean,
we're talking about the seam

18:02.290 --> 18:04.792
that's running all the way
up the edge of that blade.

18:04.792 --> 18:06.335
<i>What do you think</i>
<i>he needs to do?</i>

18:06.335 --> 18:08.504
<i>‐ Cut off the mild</i>
<i>that's coming away</i>

18:08.504 --> 18:11.299
and try to grind it back to
as good a steel as you can.

18:11.299 --> 18:12.675
<i>‐ What I'm gonna do</i>
<i>is try to do</i>

18:12.675 --> 18:14.552
<i>a very careful hollow grind</i>

18:14.552 --> 18:16.387
<i>right along the edge</i>
<i>where the delam is</i>

18:16.387 --> 18:19.223
<i>and see if I can't get</i>
<i>towards the weld as solid.</i>

18:19.223 --> 18:21.475
<i>I have to make sure</i>
<i>this knife performs.</i>

18:21.475 --> 18:23.269
I'm here to represent
the air force.

18:23.269 --> 18:25.271
‐ Bladesmiths, one hour.

18:25.271 --> 18:27.398
You have one hour remaining
in this round.

18:27.398 --> 18:28.774
<i>‐ The chance for somebody</i>
<i>to really show</i>

18:28.774 --> 18:31.652
<i>their craftsmanship</i>
<i>in knife making these days</i>

18:31.652 --> 18:34.238
<i>is really exhibiting some</i>
<i>quality work in the handle.</i>

18:34.238 --> 18:35.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:35.781 --> 18:37.950
<i>I want that</i>
<i>air force anvil so bad,</i>

18:37.950 --> 18:40.828
<i>I can almost taste it,</i>
<i>and I can feel it comin'.</i>

18:40.828 --> 18:42.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:42.455 --> 18:44.582
<i>‐ Got my pin handles drilled.</i>
<i>I mean, I'm getting there.</i>

18:44.582 --> 18:46.167
And it's somewhat
shaped like...

18:46.167 --> 18:48.419
[laughs]
Like the bolo.

18:48.419 --> 18:49.795
Oh, get in there.

18:49.795 --> 18:51.881
<i>But I was unable</i>
<i>to take care of the warp.</i>

18:51.881 --> 18:53.633
<i>The time is really pushing me.</i>

18:53.633 --> 18:54.967
<i>I need to get</i>
<i>this handle glued up,</i>

18:54.967 --> 18:56.510
<i>and then I need to get</i>
<i>this knife sharpened.</i>

18:56.510 --> 18:58.304
‐ In Matt's mind,
the whole thing is,

18:58.304 --> 18:59.805
"Make a complete knife."

18:59.805 --> 19:01.182
If you have time,
straighten it.

19:01.182 --> 19:02.892
But you don't want to end up
with a straight knife

19:02.892 --> 19:04.310
that doesn't meet parameter.

19:04.310 --> 19:05.895
<i>‐ I'm definitely worried</i>
<i>about the warp.</i>

19:05.895 --> 19:10.149
<i>It might affect the way</i>
<i>it cuts the sugarcane.</i>

19:10.149 --> 19:11.901
<i>‐ I had a big mess</i>
<i>to start with,</i>

19:11.901 --> 19:13.778
<i>but by doing a hollow grind,</i>

19:13.778 --> 19:16.072
<i>I was able to get in where</i>
<i>those welds weren't completed</i>

19:16.072 --> 19:17.531
<i>and basically able to blend</i>
<i>the steel</i>

19:17.531 --> 19:19.325
<i>and I was able to find</i>
<i>where the welds are.</i>

19:19.325 --> 19:20.785
‐ Bladesmiths,

19:20.785 --> 19:22.536
you have just
30 minutes remaining

19:22.536 --> 19:23.829
to finish your blades.

19:23.829 --> 19:25.164
<i>‐ Right now, I'm gonna work on</i>

19:25.164 --> 19:26.707
<i>getting the handle</i>
<i>finished up.</i>

19:26.707 --> 19:28.209
<i>These are chopping knives,</i>

19:28.209 --> 19:30.252
<i>so it's gotta fit comfortably</i>
<i>in the hand real well.</i>

19:30.252 --> 19:32.004
Okay, back to the blade.

19:32.004 --> 19:34.965
And then I need to put
a final edge on it.

19:34.965 --> 19:37.259
‐ 20 minutes, bladesmiths.

19:37.259 --> 19:39.053
<i>‐ I'm so focused</i>
<i>on what I'm doing,</i>

19:39.053 --> 19:40.721
<i>I'm kind of over here</i>
<i>in my own little world.</i>

19:40.721 --> 19:43.015
‐ Does Mike have a lanyard hole
through his handle?

19:43.015 --> 19:44.684
‐ I can't see a hole from here.

19:44.684 --> 19:49.730
<i>‐ I was sanding the handle,</i>
<i>just getting the pins flush.</i>

19:49.730 --> 19:51.190
‐ Uhp, there we go‐‐

19:51.190 --> 19:53.442
forgot to put the
lanyard hole in...[chuckles]

19:53.442 --> 19:55.319
<i>‐ I know</i>
<i>I drilled it in the tang,</i>

19:55.319 --> 19:57.154
<i>so it's just a question</i>
<i>at this point</i>

19:57.154 --> 19:59.490
of hoping I hit the right spot
on the drill press.

19:59.490 --> 20:01.659
<i>If it goes wrong,</i>
<i>then I could ruin my handle.</i>

20:05.204 --> 20:08.374
<i>It could crack</i>
<i>$50,000 is on the line here.</i>

20:08.374 --> 20:09.792
<i>I nailed it.</i>

20:09.792 --> 20:12.503
Crisis averted.

20:12.503 --> 20:15.548
‐ Matt‐‐he's pulling his blade
out of the clamps right now.

20:15.548 --> 20:17.133
‐ Damn.

20:17.133 --> 20:20.094
‐ Matt's got a little gaposis
right there at the ricasso.

20:20.094 --> 20:21.512
‐ Well, [bleep].

20:21.512 --> 20:23.389
The tang‐‐
it's got a slight warp,

20:23.389 --> 20:24.849
<i>and I have</i>
<i>some pretty big gaps</i>

20:24.849 --> 20:27.727
<i>between the wood</i>
<i>and the metal.</i>

20:27.727 --> 20:29.395
‐ That wood's
not very flexible.

20:29.395 --> 20:30.896
‐ This is not gonna work.

20:30.896 --> 20:32.189
The clock is counting down,

20:32.189 --> 20:34.817
<i>and there's only about</i>
<i>ten minutes left.</i>

20:34.817 --> 20:37.570
‐ At this point,
mix some of the sawdust up

20:37.570 --> 20:40.406
with some of that epoxy
and make some gap filler.

20:40.406 --> 20:43.617
<i>‐ I decide to clamp</i>
<i>everything back together,</i>

20:43.617 --> 20:46.203
apply some more glue,
and then go ahead

20:46.203 --> 20:47.747
and just go back
to the grinder,

20:47.747 --> 20:50.416
<i>and I'm hoping for the best.</i>

20:50.416 --> 20:52.418
‐ Two minutes, bladesmiths.

20:52.418 --> 20:53.919
<i>‐ There was only</i>
<i>a couple minutes left.</i>

20:53.919 --> 20:55.796
<i>Etched, I forgot.</i>
<i>Etched.</i>

20:55.796 --> 20:58.758
And it finally hit me that I'm
supposed to etch this blade.

20:58.758 --> 21:00.593
<i>So, I knew I had to get it</i>
<i>over to the ferric chloride</i>

21:00.593 --> 21:02.136
<i>and get it done.</i>

21:02.136 --> 21:04.221
If I don't get this etch,
it could be what sends me home.

21:04.221 --> 21:06.182
‐ Five, four,

21:06.182 --> 21:09.059
three, two, one.

21:09.059 --> 21:10.603
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

21:10.603 --> 21:13.189
Drop your tools.
Stop what you're doing.

21:13.189 --> 21:15.775
This second round
of competition is over.

21:15.775 --> 21:18.027
Good job.
[all applauding]

21:18.027 --> 21:19.653
<i>‐ I'm not happy with the edge.</i>

21:19.653 --> 21:21.739
<i>I'm not completely happy</i>
<i>with the handle.</i>

21:21.739 --> 21:24.325
<i>I think it is testable,</i>
<i>but I'm not 100% confident</i>

21:24.325 --> 21:27.286
that I'm gonna
survive this round.

21:27.286 --> 21:30.289
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the flight helmet chop.

21:30.289 --> 21:32.666
To test the strength and
durability of your bolo blades,

21:32.666 --> 21:34.794
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

21:34.794 --> 21:36.879
I'm going to be bashing them
into these flight helmets.

21:36.879 --> 21:38.506
<i>[fighter planes whoosh]</i>

21:38.506 --> 21:39.799
Remember, I don't really care

21:39.799 --> 21:41.467
what happens
to these brain buckets.

21:41.467 --> 21:43.594
It's what happens to your bolos
that really counts.

21:43.594 --> 21:44.887
Mike, you're up first.
You ready?

21:44.887 --> 21:46.847
‐ Let's crack this nut.
‐ All right.

21:46.847 --> 21:49.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:49.016 --> 21:50.392
<i>‐ I'm probably dehydrated,</i>

21:50.392 --> 21:52.520
<i>or I'd be sweating bullets</i>
<i>right now.</i>

21:52.520 --> 21:55.356
<i>These helmets are made</i>
<i>to survive impacts‐‐</i>

21:55.356 --> 21:58.067
<i>hard impacts,</i>
<i>airplane impacts.</i>

21:58.067 --> 21:59.985
My knife may not
stand a chance.

21:59.985 --> 22:06.992
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:11.622 --> 22:13.457
[exhales]

22:13.457 --> 22:16.126
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:16.126 --> 22:19.171
‐ Well, Mike, your blade
held up really well,

22:19.171 --> 22:21.632
and there's no evidence

22:21.632 --> 22:23.092
that this edge
has seen a helmet.

22:23.092 --> 22:24.677
‐ [exhales]

22:24.677 --> 22:27.596
‐ The one major issue I have is
just the size of this handle.

22:27.596 --> 22:30.349
It's a little narrow in
this dimension for my hand,

22:30.349 --> 22:32.768
which makes it
a little bit round and rolly.

22:32.768 --> 22:34.186
But all in all,

22:34.186 --> 22:36.772
it all held up really well
to the test, so well done.

22:36.772 --> 22:39.024
‐ Thank you.

22:39.024 --> 22:41.151
‐ So Matt,
you see what we're up to.

22:41.151 --> 22:42.903
How you feeling?
‐ Little nervous.

22:42.903 --> 22:44.738
‐ [laughs]
All right.

22:44.738 --> 22:46.574
Well, we're gonna do it anyway.

22:46.574 --> 22:48.576
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:48.576 --> 22:50.244
<i>‐ My heart's just poundin'.</i>

22:50.244 --> 22:52.580
<i>I'm feeling like</i>
<i>my handle might break</i>

22:52.580 --> 22:54.123
<i>over this aviator helmet.</i>

22:54.123 --> 22:56.166
<i>I can just hear it hitting</i>
<i>the floor right now.</i>

22:56.166 --> 23:03.173
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:06.051 --> 23:08.971
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:08.971 --> 23:11.265
‐ [exhales]

23:11.265 --> 23:13.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:13.559 --> 23:16.312
‐ Well, Matt,
your edge held up really well.

23:16.312 --> 23:17.897
It's still sharp.

23:17.897 --> 23:20.232
The big issue
I have is the handle.

23:20.232 --> 23:22.401
All of the pins
have come loose.

23:22.401 --> 23:24.403
The handle itself...
[hollow tapping]

23:24.403 --> 23:25.905
Isn't really glued in place.

23:25.905 --> 23:27.823
Would've been worthwhile
to take more time

23:27.823 --> 23:29.700
fixing this warp.

23:29.700 --> 23:32.494
But that aside,
it all held together well,

23:32.494 --> 23:33.829
so good job.

23:33.829 --> 23:34.997
‐ Thank you.

23:34.997 --> 23:36.457
‐ Joe, you're up.
How you feeling?

23:36.457 --> 23:39.251
‐ I'm as ready as I can be.
‐ Me too.

23:39.251 --> 23:40.669
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:40.669 --> 23:42.546
<i>‐ In order to get rid</i>
<i>of my delaminations,</i>

23:42.546 --> 23:44.882
<i>I had to put in</i>
<i>a hollow grind.</i>

23:44.882 --> 23:46.550
<i>So I'm convinced that</i>
<i>I'm gonna take some damage</i>

23:46.550 --> 23:47.885
<i>in the strength test.</i>

23:47.885 --> 23:49.511
<i>The question is,</i>
<i>how much damage</i>

23:49.511 --> 23:51.096
<i>and how much will</i>
<i>it affect my ability</i>

23:51.096 --> 23:52.806
moving forward in the
sharpness test.

24:06.862 --> 24:11.158
‐ Well, Joe, your blade here
suffered chipping.

24:11.158 --> 24:14.036
<i>Got a big, sort of</i>
<i>dime‐radius chip</i>

24:14.036 --> 24:16.622
<i>and then the rest of it</i>
<i>is all chipped as well.</i>

24:16.622 --> 24:18.707
I think that when you were
chasing this delamination,

24:18.707 --> 24:22.211
you ended up with an edge
that's on the thinner side.

24:22.211 --> 24:25.130
Aside from your blade,
the handle is a good size,

24:25.130 --> 24:27.383
good dimension.

24:27.383 --> 24:29.677
I like the contouring.

24:29.677 --> 24:33.305
But there's just no denying
this chipping on the edge here.

24:33.305 --> 24:34.640
‐ Yes, sir.

24:34.640 --> 24:36.350
‐ Gentlemen, next up
is the sharpness test.

24:36.350 --> 24:37.935
With that, I give you to Doug.

24:37.935 --> 24:40.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:40.354 --> 24:41.981
‐ All right, bladesmiths...
[chuckles]

24:41.981 --> 24:45.025
This is the sugarcane slice.

24:45.025 --> 24:46.318
To test the sharpness
of your weapon,

24:46.318 --> 24:47.987
I will cut across
these sugarcanes.

24:47.987 --> 24:49.571
Mike, you're up first.
You ready for this?

24:49.571 --> 24:52.533
‐ Absolutely.
‐ Let's do this.

24:52.533 --> 24:55.160
‐ I'm just praying and hoping
there's no problems.

24:55.160 --> 25:02.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:04.837 --> 25:06.296
[exhales]

25:06.296 --> 25:07.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:07.673 --> 25:09.174
‐ All right, Mike.

25:09.174 --> 25:12.720
Your edge cut easily
through this sugarcane.

25:12.720 --> 25:15.723
It's light,
it's fast, it's sharp,

25:15.723 --> 25:18.475
and most importantly,
it will cut.

25:18.475 --> 25:19.852
‐ Yes.

25:19.852 --> 25:21.562
‐ All right, Matt.
Your turn, sir. You ready?

25:21.562 --> 25:22.855
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

25:22.855 --> 25:29.862
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:38.746 --> 25:41.248
[sugarcane thunks]

25:41.248 --> 25:42.583
‐ [exhales]

25:42.583 --> 25:44.168
‐ Nice.
‐ Thanks.

25:44.168 --> 25:46.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:46.045 --> 25:49.256
‐ First up, the handle‐‐
it's loosened a lot.

25:49.256 --> 25:51.050
<i>There's a little crack,</i>
<i>and it's starting to open up</i>

25:51.050 --> 25:52.509
<i>where I can see it.</i>

25:52.509 --> 25:55.846
But despite the severe warp
that you have right here,

25:55.846 --> 25:58.557
your blade is strong,
it's sharp,

25:58.557 --> 26:00.851
and most importantly,
it will cut.

26:00.851 --> 26:02.936
‐ Awesome.
‐ All right, chief.

26:02.936 --> 26:04.354
You're next. You ready?
‐ Yes, sir.

26:04.354 --> 26:05.856
‐ Let's do this.

26:05.856 --> 26:07.816
<i>‐ I know my only chance</i>
<i>of moving on at this point</i>

26:07.816 --> 26:09.610
is my blade has
to perform very well.

26:09.610 --> 26:16.658
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:21.413 --> 26:23.582
‐ Good job.
‐ Thanks.

26:23.582 --> 26:25.667
‐ All right, chief, let's talk
about your bolo here.

26:25.667 --> 26:29.296
Your edge‐‐you have some
missing pieces right here.

26:29.296 --> 26:32.007
But the edge
is sharp enough to cut.

26:32.007 --> 26:33.967
It's wieldable.
You have a good balance here

26:33.967 --> 26:36.136
because it's got
a good handle to hold onto.

26:36.136 --> 26:38.680
More important, sir, it'll cut.

26:38.680 --> 26:40.974
‐ Thank you.

26:40.974 --> 26:43.769
‐ Airmen, the judges have
completed their deliberation

26:43.769 --> 26:47.106
and it's time for one of you
smiths to leave The Forge.

26:47.106 --> 26:49.274
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

26:49.274 --> 26:52.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:52.611 --> 26:54.947
Joe, your blade
didn't make the cut.

26:54.947 --> 26:56.448
Ben Abbott's
gonna tell you why.

26:56.448 --> 26:59.576
‐ Joe, you had a large
delamination in your blade,

26:59.576 --> 27:03.122
and in chasing that, you ended
up making the edge very thin.

27:03.122 --> 27:05.374
And it took a lot of damage
in the strength test,

27:05.374 --> 27:07.793
and it's for that reason
we're sending you home.

27:07.793 --> 27:09.169
‐ Yes, sir.

27:09.169 --> 27:11.922
‐ Chief, please surrender
your blade.

27:11.922 --> 27:14.091
<i>‐ I'm disappointed in myself</i>
<i>that I didn't do a better job</i>

27:14.091 --> 27:16.051
in the first round
and wasn't able to make

27:16.051 --> 27:17.636
the corrections
that needed to be made,

27:17.636 --> 27:20.139
<i>but I feel really good about</i>
<i>the two smiths moving forward</i>

27:20.139 --> 27:21.723
<i>representing the air force.</i>

27:21.723 --> 27:23.600
I may not be a
"Forged in Fire" champion,

27:23.600 --> 27:24.852
<i>but I had the opportunity</i>
<i>to come here</i>

27:24.852 --> 27:26.270
<i>and show some of my skills.</i>

27:26.270 --> 27:29.064
I'm walking out
with my head held high.

27:29.064 --> 27:31.108
‐ Mike, Matt, congratulations.

27:31.108 --> 27:33.443
You've made it to the
next phase in this operation,

27:33.443 --> 27:35.320
which means we're sending you
back to your home forges

27:35.320 --> 27:37.614
to recreate
this iconic weapon...

27:37.614 --> 27:40.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:40.701 --> 27:44.538
The United States Air Force
non‐commissioned officer sword.

27:44.538 --> 27:47.082
‐ [exhales]

27:47.082 --> 27:49.376
<i>‐ Despite having</i>
<i>no historical use of swords,</i>

27:49.376 --> 27:52.004
<i>the US Air Force</i>
<i>utilizes ceremonial weapons</i>

27:52.004 --> 27:53.839
<i>like the non‐commissioned</i>
<i>officer sword</i>

27:53.839 --> 27:56.216
<i>as a nod to their roots</i>
<i>in the army.</i>

27:56.216 --> 27:58.010
<i>Based on the</i>
<i>European pillow sword,</i>

27:58.010 --> 28:00.637
<i>the NCO is a lightning‐fast</i>
<i>stabbing weapon that</i>

28:00.637 --> 28:03.974
<i>can be unleashed with lethal</i>
<i>precision in able hands.</i>

28:03.974 --> 28:06.685
<i>Small, looped quillions</i>
<i>form the NCO's crossguard</i>

28:06.685 --> 28:08.312
<i>and its flattened blade</i>
<i>extends to a point</i>

28:08.312 --> 28:10.439
<i>about 28 inches away.</i>

28:10.439 --> 28:13.066
<i>The NCO sword's slick design</i>
<i>is the ideal symbol</i>

28:13.066 --> 28:17.029
<i>for the air force's stealthy,</i>
<i>enemy‐vanquishing power.</i>

28:17.029 --> 28:18.906
<i>‐ The challenge here is gonna</i>
<i>be making a small sword</i>

28:18.906 --> 28:21.700
<i>that's gonna be strong,</i>
<i>that's not gonna bend, warp.</i>

28:21.700 --> 28:24.453
So yeah,
it's gonna be a hard one.

28:24.453 --> 28:26.330
<i>‐ Gentlemen, your swords</i>
<i>must be double‐edged.</i>

28:26.330 --> 28:28.957
<i>You must have a ball pommel</i>
<i>and a lobed crossguard.</i>

28:28.957 --> 28:30.709
You'll have four days
at your home forges

28:30.709 --> 28:32.210
in which to complete
this challenge.

28:32.210 --> 28:34.129
At the end of four days,
you'll return and present

28:34.129 --> 28:36.381
your swords to our panel
of expert judges.

28:36.381 --> 28:38.216
And after they've put 'em
through the paces,

28:38.216 --> 28:40.594
they'll move one of you on
to our final

28:40.594 --> 28:42.888
Battle of the Branches
competition.

28:42.888 --> 28:44.556
By the way,

28:44.556 --> 28:46.141
you also need to make
a scabbard for this sword.

28:46.141 --> 28:48.977
‐ [softly] Oh, man.
‐ I'm just messing with you.

28:48.977 --> 28:51.563
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

28:51.563 --> 28:53.732
‐ Good luck, brother.

28:53.732 --> 28:55.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:55.901 --> 28:57.319
<i>‐ It's day one.</i>

28:57.319 --> 28:59.488
<i>Feels great to be back here</i>
<i>in my home forge.</i>

28:59.488 --> 29:01.406
<i>For this blade,</i>
<i>I'm gonna be using Damascus,</i>

29:01.406 --> 29:03.867
and I'm gonna try to put
in a twist just for fun.

29:03.867 --> 29:06.745
<i>A lot of air force ties in</i>
<i>how I live my life day to day,</i>

29:06.745 --> 29:09.581
and this challenge
was no exception.

29:09.581 --> 29:11.291
<i>There's a lot of firsts</i>
<i>for me on this blade.</i>

29:11.291 --> 29:12.960
<i>I've never done</i>
<i>Damascus this long.</i>

29:12.960 --> 29:14.753
<i>I've never heat‐treated</i>
<i>anything this long.</i>

29:14.753 --> 29:17.005
<i>I've never made a crossguard</i>
<i>like this before.</i>

29:17.005 --> 29:18.799
<i>It's gonna be a bit</i>
<i>stressful for me.</i>

29:18.799 --> 29:21.426
None of my welds popped, so
at least it's a solid billet.

29:21.426 --> 29:23.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.261 --> 29:26.348
<i>So, we won't know for sure</i>
<i>until we're grinding into it,</i>

29:26.348 --> 29:29.851
<i>but I'm fairly certain</i>
<i>it was a successful twist.</i>

29:29.851 --> 29:31.478
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>we have any inclusions.</i>

29:31.478 --> 29:34.106
I think it's gonna
look pretty good.

29:34.106 --> 29:36.316
So I've got 16 layers
now in this billet.

29:36.316 --> 29:37.526
<i>I've got it drawn out enough</i>

29:37.526 --> 29:39.277
<i>I can cut it</i>
<i>into three sections,</i>

29:39.277 --> 29:42.656
<i>stack it back on itself,</i>
<i>for a total of 48 layers.</i>

29:42.656 --> 29:44.241
<i>This is gonna be</i>
<i>one of the longest things</i>

29:44.241 --> 29:45.826
<i>I've ever forged,</i>
<i>so keeping it straight</i>

29:45.826 --> 29:47.202
<i>might be a little bit</i>
<i>of a challenge,</i>

29:47.202 --> 29:48.662
<i>especially</i>
<i>with the twist in it.</i>

29:48.662 --> 29:50.372
<i>That could cause</i>
<i>some things to warp.</i>

29:50.372 --> 29:52.624
All in all,
a solid finish for day one.

29:52.624 --> 29:55.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:55.502 --> 29:57.671
<i>‐ Now that</i>
<i>I'm one two airmen left,</i>

29:57.671 --> 29:59.715
I definitely want to be,
you know, the one that

29:59.715 --> 30:01.383
shows that the air force
has what it takes

30:01.383 --> 30:04.469
to win the "Forged in Fire"
branch competition.

30:04.469 --> 30:06.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:06.096 --> 30:09.641
<i>The plan for today is to draw</i>
<i>the 1084 round stock out.</i>

30:09.641 --> 30:11.309
[machine whirring]

30:11.309 --> 30:13.228
<i>I'm just gonna draw a line</i>
<i>on the floor</i>

30:13.228 --> 30:16.273
to give me an idea of how far
I'm drawing it out.

30:16.273 --> 30:18.817
<i>To start,</i>
<i>the 1084 steel was 20 inches.</i>

30:18.817 --> 30:21.319
<i>I gotta draw it out</i>
<i>to about 35 inches</i>

30:21.319 --> 30:24.322
<i>to get the crossguard,</i>
<i>the handle, and the pommel.</i>

30:24.322 --> 30:27.200
I still gotta draw it out
quite a bit, thin it down.

30:27.200 --> 30:31.246
<i>This 27 to 28‐inch sword</i>
<i>is gonna be interesting</i>

30:31.246 --> 30:32.998
keeping it straight.

30:32.998 --> 30:34.374
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.374 --> 30:36.209
<i>‐ Today is quench day.</i>

30:36.209 --> 30:37.711
First things first,

30:37.711 --> 30:40.422
<i>I think I better tackle</i>
<i>modifying the heat‐treat oven</i>

30:40.422 --> 30:42.841
<i>so that it can accommodate</i>
<i>such a large blade.</i>

30:42.841 --> 30:44.634
<i>I like to use this because</i>

30:44.634 --> 30:47.763
<i>I can heat‐treat my blade</i>
<i>to a set temperature.</i>

30:47.763 --> 30:49.556
We can just try to make sure
that the heat soaks

30:49.556 --> 30:51.183
all the way down the blade.

30:51.183 --> 30:53.769
<i>Consistency is kinda key</i>
<i>to performance,</i>

30:53.769 --> 30:55.103
<i>so I want the grain structure</i>

30:55.103 --> 30:56.688
<i>to be the same</i>
<i>all the way through.</i>

30:56.688 --> 30:58.190
<i>That's what I'm hoping</i>
<i>to accomplish.</i>

30:58.190 --> 30:59.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:59.775 --> 31:02.778
Yeah, that's just not
gonna work for me.

31:02.778 --> 31:05.197
So, I'm gonna have to do it
in the forge.

31:05.197 --> 31:07.157
<i>It's much harder to keep</i>
<i>a consistent temperature</i>

31:07.157 --> 31:08.742
<i>across the entire blade,</i>

31:08.742 --> 31:10.869
<i>but it's what I have</i>
<i>to go with.</i>

31:10.869 --> 31:12.704
<i>I've never quenched</i>
<i>anything this large.</i>

31:12.704 --> 31:14.081
<i>I'm kind of excited</i>
<i>and a little scared</i>

31:14.081 --> 31:15.582
<i>to see how it's gonna go.</i>

31:15.582 --> 31:21.797
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:21.797 --> 31:23.381
<i>It definitely sabered,</i>

31:23.381 --> 31:25.675
<i>which meant</i>
<i>it curves off to the side.</i>

31:25.675 --> 31:27.094
<i>Well, that's what</i>
<i>I gotta struggle with</i>

31:27.094 --> 31:29.888
and decide whether or not
I need to try to just

31:29.888 --> 31:33.517
redo the heat treat,
quench it, straighten it out.

31:33.517 --> 31:36.186
<i>I think I'm just gonna</i>
<i>grind it, take the gamble.</i>

31:36.186 --> 31:38.063
<i>I'm gonna hope that</i>
<i>it doesn't cost me in the end.</i>

31:38.063 --> 31:39.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:39.815 --> 31:41.900
<i>‐ It is ‐18 outside right now,</i>

31:41.900 --> 31:45.487
<i>so I'm ready to get inside</i>
<i>and turn this forge on.</i>

31:45.487 --> 31:47.614
So yesterday,
I got the blade drawn out.

31:47.614 --> 31:49.950
<i>This morning,</i>
<i>we're going for the quench.</i>

31:49.950 --> 31:53.161
<i>Getting something this long</i>
<i>hot and keeping it straight</i>

31:53.161 --> 31:55.747
<i>is gonna be one of my</i>
<i>biggest challenges right now.</i>

31:55.747 --> 31:58.083
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:58.083 --> 31:59.501
<i>Now I got a warping issue.</i>

31:59.501 --> 32:00.710
[bleep].

32:00.710 --> 32:02.379
Might be
heat‐treating it again.

32:02.379 --> 32:04.089
<i>In the back of your mind,</i>
<i>you're always thinking</i>

32:04.089 --> 32:05.966
<i>"Did the heat treat</i>
<i>not go well?</i>

32:05.966 --> 32:07.300
<i>"Quenching two times?</i>

32:07.300 --> 32:09.594
<i>Will I have, you know,</i>
<i>bad grain structure?"</i>

32:09.594 --> 32:11.138
<i>I have a ton of concerns.</i>

32:11.138 --> 32:11.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:16.726 --> 32:20.313
Slight warp, but at this point,

32:20.313 --> 32:23.817
I'm definitely
not quenching again.

32:23.817 --> 32:25.277
<i>‐ It's the morning</i>
<i>of day four.</i>

32:25.277 --> 32:26.736
<i>I didn't sleep very well.</i>

32:26.736 --> 32:28.238
<i>I still need</i>
<i>to finish the pommel.</i>

32:28.238 --> 32:29.656
<i>I need to finish</i>
<i>the crossguard.</i>

32:29.656 --> 32:31.616
<i>And I haven't even</i>
<i>started the handle yet.</i>

32:31.616 --> 32:34.578
<i>I can tell we're</i>
<i>almost through, though.</i>

32:34.578 --> 32:36.121
[drill whirring]
<i>Almost there.</i>

32:36.121 --> 32:38.165
I can feel it.

32:38.165 --> 32:40.458
<i>I definitely think this</i>
<i>a blade worthy of having me</i>

32:40.458 --> 32:43.587
<i>stand at the air force anvil</i>
<i>in the final round.</i>

32:43.587 --> 32:45.839
It is an example of
how I problem solve,

32:45.839 --> 32:48.508
how I look for solutions,
and how I don't give up.

32:48.508 --> 32:51.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:51.052 --> 32:54.472
All right, that's as good
as we're gonna get.

32:54.472 --> 32:56.016
<i>‐ Day four, and today,</i>

32:56.016 --> 32:58.393
<i>I need to get the</i>
<i>crossguard fitted up,</i>

32:58.393 --> 33:00.437
<i>the handle shaped,</i>
<i>wrapped with wire,</i>

33:00.437 --> 33:03.106
<i>and then the pommel</i>
<i>assembled as well.</i>

33:03.106 --> 33:04.524
Only the handle.

33:04.524 --> 33:06.610
<i>Looking at the</i>
<i>original NCO sword,</i>

33:06.610 --> 33:08.195
I was trying to figure out
what the best way

33:08.195 --> 33:10.530
to make that
wire‐wrapped handle was.

33:10.530 --> 33:12.532
<i>Safety wire‐‐</i>
<i>we use that in the military.</i>

33:12.532 --> 33:14.326
<i>I thought that was good</i>
<i>to kinda throw a little</i>

33:14.326 --> 33:16.953
<i>air force‐ism into it‐‐</i>
<i>works perfect.</i>

33:16.953 --> 33:19.164
<i>I'm definitely nervous that</i>
<i>I have only one day left.</i>

33:19.164 --> 33:20.790
<i>In the back of your mind,</i>
<i>you're always thinking,</i>

33:20.790 --> 33:22.042
<i>"Do I have what it takes</i>

33:22.042 --> 33:23.418
<i>to move on to the</i>
<i>Battle of the Branches?"</i>

33:23.418 --> 33:25.545
I mean, that's what
it's all about.

33:25.545 --> 33:26.963
That's it.

33:26.963 --> 33:29.382
<i>May the best airman win.</i>
<i>[plane whooshes]</i>

33:29.382 --> 33:36.181
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:36.181 --> 33:38.600
‐ Mike, Matt,
welcome back to The Forge.

33:38.600 --> 33:40.227
We've sent you back
to your home forges

33:40.227 --> 33:44.356
to recreate an air force
non‐commissioned officer sword.

33:44.356 --> 33:46.775
Mike, tell us about the
construction of your sword.

33:46.775 --> 33:48.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:48.693 --> 33:51.696
<i>‐ It's a 48‐layer</i>
<i>twisted Damascus,</i>

33:51.696 --> 33:54.824
<i>wooden core handle,</i>
<i>sage green paracord wrap‐‐</i>

33:54.824 --> 33:57.994
<i>little nod to the air force‐‐</i>
<i>and a ball‐bearing pommel.</i>

33:57.994 --> 34:00.080
‐ Tell the judges
about your blade, Matt.

34:00.080 --> 34:01.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:01.748 --> 34:03.833
<i>‐ So, my blade is 1084 steel.</i>

34:03.833 --> 34:07.545
<i>I used railroad spikes</i>
<i>to make the crossguard.</i>

34:07.545 --> 34:10.465
<i>A wooden handle with</i>
<i>a safety wire wrap,</i>

34:10.465 --> 34:14.094
<i>and then the pommel is</i>
<i>a railroad track bolt.</i>

34:14.094 --> 34:15.679
‐ Gentlemen,
here's what's at stake‐‐

34:15.679 --> 34:18.223
the air force anvil in
our Battle of the Branches

34:18.223 --> 34:20.433
final competition,
and hopefully,

34:20.433 --> 34:22.018
a check for $50,000

34:22.018 --> 34:24.312
if you come out
as the champion in that.

34:24.312 --> 34:25.939
And you'll be bringing
the title of

34:25.939 --> 34:29.109
"Forged in Fire" champion
back home to the air force.

34:29.109 --> 34:30.277
All right?

34:30.277 --> 34:31.695
Your weapons will
now be put through

34:31.695 --> 34:33.113
a series of three tests.

34:33.113 --> 34:35.448
And up first, the KEAL test.

34:35.448 --> 34:37.117
Doug?

34:37.117 --> 34:40.370
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:40.370 --> 34:41.621
‐ All right, airmen.

34:41.621 --> 34:43.498
I will take your weapon
and deliver some thrusts

34:43.498 --> 34:45.292
and slashes
on this ballistics dummy.

34:45.292 --> 34:46.459
<i>[plane whooshes]</i>

34:46.459 --> 34:48.086
Mike, you're up first.
You ready?

34:48.086 --> 34:49.921
‐ Absolutely. Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

34:49.921 --> 34:51.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:51.715 --> 34:53.008
<i>‐ I'm standing here</i>
<i>really nervous.</i>

34:53.008 --> 34:54.509
<i>I don't know what to expect,</i>

34:54.509 --> 34:56.303
<i>I don't know how</i>
<i>my sword's gonna do.</i>

34:56.303 --> 35:03.268
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:14.195 --> 35:16.448
[exhales]

35:16.448 --> 35:19.117
Oh...
[laughs]

35:19.117 --> 35:22.454
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:22.454 --> 35:25.332
‐ All right, Mike...[laughs]
It's a very light sword.

35:25.332 --> 35:27.542
Because of that,
you can move with it.

35:27.542 --> 35:30.879
Now, your tip allows
for nice thrust.

35:30.879 --> 35:34.549
With your edge, it slices.
I can feel every cut in there.

35:34.549 --> 35:37.594
But more importantly,
it will KEAL.

35:37.594 --> 35:39.137
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Matt, your turn.

35:39.137 --> 35:40.347
You ready, sir?

35:40.347 --> 35:41.765
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

35:41.765 --> 35:43.433
<i>‐ You know,</i>
<i>I have this vision that</i>

35:43.433 --> 35:45.435
my blade's gonna slice
this thing in half,

35:45.435 --> 35:46.895
<i>but then I also have</i>
<i>this vision that</i>

35:46.895 --> 35:48.313
<i>it's gonna bounce off</i>
<i>and fall on the floor.</i>

35:48.313 --> 35:50.565
I'm kind of nervous
at this point.

35:50.565 --> 35:57.614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:59.282 --> 36:00.533
[softly]
Nice.

36:00.533 --> 36:07.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:09.876 --> 36:11.252
‐ [exhales]

36:11.252 --> 36:13.380
[chuckles]

36:13.380 --> 36:15.965
‐ All right, Matt, let's talk
about your blade here.

36:15.965 --> 36:18.885
The edge that you have here
is very sharp.

36:18.885 --> 36:21.763
The point punctures nicely.

36:21.763 --> 36:25.016
But most importantly, sir,
it will KEAL.

36:25.016 --> 36:26.851
‐ Awesome, thank you.
‐ All right.

36:26.851 --> 36:30.563
Next stop, the strength test.
For that, we have Ben.

36:30.563 --> 36:32.148
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:32.148 --> 36:33.566
‐ Hello, bladesmiths.

36:33.566 --> 36:34.901
To test the strength and
durability of your swords,

36:34.901 --> 36:36.444
as well as their
overall construction,

36:36.444 --> 36:37.904
I'll be bashing them
into this propeller.

36:37.904 --> 36:40.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:40.031 --> 36:41.408
Mike, you're up first.
You ready?

36:41.408 --> 36:43.243
‐ [sighs] No.
‐ [laughs]

36:43.243 --> 36:46.413
We're gonna do it anyway.
‐ All right.

36:46.413 --> 36:47.831
<i>I don't know what this</i>
<i>propeller is made of‐‐</i>

36:47.831 --> 36:49.207
<i>could be steel.</i>

36:49.207 --> 36:50.959
That's what's got me
terrified right now‐‐

36:50.959 --> 36:52.961
<i>that the sword is either</i>
<i>gonna bend or break.</i>

36:55.130 --> 36:56.589
It's super thin.

36:56.589 --> 37:02.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:02.303 --> 37:03.763
[exhales]

37:03.763 --> 37:10.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:15.191 --> 37:17.444
[propeller clatters]

37:17.444 --> 37:19.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:19.446 --> 37:21.197
‐ Good job.
‐ [chuckles] It's good.

37:21.197 --> 37:23.992
‐ Well, Mike,
your blade held up great.

37:23.992 --> 37:25.827
The only issue
I have with it is that

37:25.827 --> 37:27.829
I would really like
this pommel to be bigger.

37:27.829 --> 37:30.290
If the pommel were bigger,
it would give me a stop.

37:30.290 --> 37:32.333
But it's got a nice weight.

37:32.333 --> 37:34.169
It's still sharp
as when it started.

37:34.169 --> 37:36.337
Really well done.
‐ Thank you so much.

37:36.337 --> 37:37.964
‐ Matt, you're up.
What are you thinking?

37:37.964 --> 37:39.340
‐ Ready.
‐ All right.

37:39.340 --> 37:46.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.643 --> 37:57.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:07.035 --> 38:10.163
[propeller clatters]
‐ That's badass.

38:10.163 --> 38:13.416
‐ Well, Matt,
your blade held up great.

38:13.416 --> 38:14.918
It's still sharp.

38:14.918 --> 38:16.628
This is a much heavier sword,

38:16.628 --> 38:20.548
but the biggest issue I have is
with the crossguard and back.

38:20.548 --> 38:23.885
Your crossguard is loose.
It wiggles.

38:23.885 --> 38:26.471
And also your
wire wrap is loose.

38:26.471 --> 38:29.098
But it's all in one piece.

38:29.098 --> 38:31.017
It did a heck of a thing
on that propeller. Well done.

38:31.017 --> 38:32.894
‐ Thank you.
‐ Well, we're not finished yet.

38:32.894 --> 38:34.312
Next up is the sharpness test,

38:34.312 --> 38:35.688
and for that,
I give you to Doug.

38:35.688 --> 38:39.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:39.442 --> 38:42.028
‐ All right, airmen.
To test the edge of your blade,

38:42.028 --> 38:45.365
I'm going to be cutting
across these harnesses.

38:45.365 --> 38:47.492
I'm looking for clean cuts.

38:47.492 --> 38:49.118
Mike, you're first.
You ready for this?

38:49.118 --> 38:50.829
‐ Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

38:50.829 --> 38:57.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:04.843 --> 39:08.054
[wooden thunk]

39:08.054 --> 39:09.722
‐ Good job.
‐ Thank you, it was good.

39:09.722 --> 39:11.850
‐ Sharp.
‐ All right, Mike.

39:11.850 --> 39:13.351
Light in flight,

39:13.351 --> 39:15.270
and sharp enough to
cut through the harness.

39:15.270 --> 39:16.938
It will cut.
‐ Thank you, sir.

39:16.938 --> 39:19.524
‐ Good job.
‐ Thanks, man.

39:19.524 --> 39:21.109
‐ All right, Matt.
Your turn, sir. You ready?

39:21.109 --> 39:22.443
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

39:22.443 --> 39:23.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:23.987 --> 39:26.114
<i>‐ I really want to be able</i>
<i>to represent the air force.</i>

39:26.114 --> 39:27.615
I need my blade
to cut right through

39:27.615 --> 39:29.075
these straps like butter.

39:29.075 --> 39:36.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:39.669 --> 39:40.879
‐ Man.

39:40.879 --> 39:43.381
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:43.381 --> 39:45.508
‐ All right, Matt, let's talk
about your blade here.

39:45.508 --> 39:47.051
It's kind of heavy.

39:47.051 --> 39:50.763
It's so forward in its weight
that on this slash,

39:50.763 --> 39:52.348
you see the last 6 inches‐‐

39:52.348 --> 39:54.350
it just scratched
the back of the harness.

39:54.350 --> 39:55.935
But on the backhand swing,

39:55.935 --> 39:58.605
which is going all the way
through, it cut the harness.

39:58.605 --> 39:59.939
But your weapon, sir,
it will cut.

39:59.939 --> 40:01.649
‐ Thanks.
‐ Good job, man.

40:01.649 --> 40:02.942
‐ Thanks.
‐ Coming into this,

40:02.942 --> 40:04.861
Matt and I promised each other
that our goal was

40:04.861 --> 40:06.362
<i>to make each other earn it.</i>

40:06.362 --> 40:08.197
<i>He's a heck of a smith, so...</i>

40:08.197 --> 40:10.450
<i>it's in the judges' hands now.</i>

40:10.450 --> 40:11.826
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:11.826 --> 40:14.579
‐ Mike, Matt, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

40:14.579 --> 40:16.664
They've made their
final decision about

40:16.664 --> 40:18.458
which of you will
move forward to our

40:18.458 --> 40:20.668
Battle of the Branches
final competition

40:20.668 --> 40:23.504
to represent the air force
at the air force's anvil.

40:23.504 --> 40:25.465
The bladesmith
moving forward is...

40:25.465 --> 40:28.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.885 --> 40:30.637
Mike.
Congratulations.

40:30.637 --> 40:32.555
‐ Thank you.

40:32.555 --> 40:34.515
‐ Matt, first of all,
thank you for your service.

40:34.515 --> 40:36.726
You have a beautiful sword
that did quite well,

40:36.726 --> 40:38.853
but we based our decision
on the fact that

40:38.853 --> 40:41.314
your guard came loose.
The weight of your sword

40:41.314 --> 40:44.067
and the wire wrapping
is also loose.

40:44.067 --> 40:45.985
That's the reason
we're sending you home.

40:45.985 --> 40:48.780
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Matt, at this time,

40:48.780 --> 40:51.616
I'ma have to ask you to
please surrender your blade.

40:51.616 --> 40:52.909
<i>‐ I feel good.</i>

40:52.909 --> 40:55.203
<i>No matter what, I mean,</i>
<i>I'm glad I made it here.</i>

40:55.203 --> 40:56.788
‐ Good job.
‐ Thank you.

40:56.788 --> 40:59.499
I'm proud of myself, for sure.
Thanks, man.

40:59.499 --> 41:01.167
<i>Mike's gonna represent</i>
<i>the air force well.</i>

41:01.167 --> 41:03.127
<i>He's got a lot of people</i>
<i>rooting for him, me as well,</i>

41:03.127 --> 41:05.713
and he's a good bladesmith,
so good luck.

41:05.713 --> 41:09.592
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:09.592 --> 41:12.720
‐ Mike, they said you're only
as good as your competition,

41:12.720 --> 41:15.348
and you overcame
a fantastic competitor

41:15.348 --> 41:16.683
<i>to move forward</i>
<i>in this competition</i>

41:16.683 --> 41:20.186
<i>to represent the entire branch</i>
<i>of the air force</i>

41:20.186 --> 41:21.896
<i>at our Battle of the Branches</i>
<i>competition.</i>

41:21.896 --> 41:24.190
How do you feel?
‐ Feels amazing.

41:24.190 --> 41:27.068
‐ Please present your blade
to the judges.

41:27.068 --> 41:28.945
<i>‐ I can't believe</i>
<i>I'm the air force champion.</i>

41:28.945 --> 41:30.822
I'm looking forward to
showing the rest of the DoD

41:30.822 --> 41:32.240
what we've got.

41:32.240 --> 41:33.658
<i>There's a lot of added</i>
<i>pressure moving forward.</i>

41:33.658 --> 41:35.076
<i>Now I'm competing against</i>
<i>the army, the navy,</i>

41:35.076 --> 41:36.494
<i>and the marine corps.</i>

41:36.494 --> 41:37.912
<i>And we've got a little bit</i>
<i>of a rivalry going on,</i>

41:37.912 --> 41:40.081
so you better bring it,
'cause you know I'm going to.

41:40.081 --> 41:46.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>
